$ATIP  I think the most important aspects of the recent Jefferies and Hedgeye comments are: 

1. Evidence of increased patient traffic 
2. Evidence of increased hiring and reduced employee attrition

It’s well reported that $ATIP was ruthlessly brutal in cutting costs during Covid. That behavior caused employee attrition to spike to ~80% in late 2020.

A silver lining is that there is likely a bigly amount of operating leverage baked into $ATIP that should more than offset higher employees expenses over time, assuming of course that employment and patient visits continue to improve

Note that the smaller clinics that comprise the bulk of the PT market have the same labor cost issues, without the scale benefits of the largest PT practices. Smaller size also limits a clinic’s ability to earn high CMS MIPS scores high enough to offset CMS’s expected deep cuts in PT reimbursements, unlike $ATIP who earns high MIPS scores. 

PT industry consolidation should accelerate at some point Bullish
